    {
      "id": "n4iormrf",
      "x": 1456,
      "y": 2653,
      "w": 320,
      "h": 483,
      "group": null,
      "data": {
        "date": "2025-09-19",
        "title": "Neuropolitics",
        "type": "Finding",
        "action": "Exploring",
        "mainArea": "Speculation",
        "areas": [
          "Neuroscience",
          "Biopolitics",
          "Society studies",
          "Critical theory",
          "Socio-political"
        ],
        "tags": [],
        "desc": "Neuroscience, AI, and politics are at the center of contemporary debate. It's a hot and plausible topic. It implies a strong cognitive conflict: more knowledge and transparency on the one hand, more surveillance and manipulation on the other. It opens the door to tangible devices (bracelets, helmets, pills, algorithms), which can be prototyped in credible but also disturbing ways. Politics affects everyone, and a project that questions freedom of thought and voting generates immediate discussion.",
        "links": [
          "https://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/neuropolitica_(altro)/"
        ],
        "files": []
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "nkhzwryp",
      "x": 1459.3102180018955,
      "y": 3177,
      "w": 320,
      "h": 748,
      "group": null,
      "data": {
        "date": "2025-09-19",
        "title": "Learning",
        "type": "Finding",
        "action": null,
        "mainArea": null,
        "areas": [
          "Neuroscience",
          "Society studies"
        ],
        "tags": [],
        "desc": "The learning phase is crucial for cognitive development and conflict: Children actively construct their cognitive schemas; it is during this phase that lasting ways of dealing with dissonance are defined.\nExposing children to cognitive discrepancies creates a state of imbalance that pushes them toward accommodating new schemas. \nWorking in groups with different ideas exposes children to their first meaningful experiences of cognitive disagreement. These differences influence whether conflict is productive or counterproductive.\nParents transmit values, explanations, and strategies (explicit and implicit) that shape how children deal with dissonance.",
        "links": [
          "https://www.alessandrogrussu.it/txt/Cooperativo.pdf",
          "https://files.eric.ed.gov/fulltext/EJ1391444.pdf#:~:text=students%20need%20to%20admit%20that,in%20science%20learning%2C%20students%20need",
          "https://thesis.unipd.it/retrieve/c3ca2f2c-d6b3-4564-9ee4-33700ee19363/TESI_Ilenia_Balzano_PDF_A.pdf#:~:text=di%3A%20razza%2C%20religione%2C%20etnia%20e,FI%20utilizzano%20pi%C3%B9%20spesso%20argomentazioni",
          "https://indianmentalhealth.com/pdf/2022/vol9-issue3/4-Review-Paper-2.pdf#:~:text=Believed%20that%20cognitive%20conflict%20due,with%20an%20urge%20to%20change",
          "https://www.scirp.org/reference/referencespapers?referenceid=738315"
        ],
        "files": []
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "nai1yave",
      "x": 1456,
      "y": 1310,
      "w": 320,
      "h": 738,
      "group": null,
      "data": {
        "date": "2025-09-19",
        "title": "Cognitive Hedonia",
        "type": "Finding",
        "action": null,
        "mainArea": null,
        "areas": [
          "Neuroscience",
          "Human-computer interaction",
          "Biopolitics",
          "Cyberpsychology",
          "Critical technology studies",
          "Media studies",
          "Society studies"
        ],
        "tags": [],
        "desc": "Mark Fisher coined the term \"depressive hedonia\" to describe a modern paradox: people who obsessively seek pleasure but never get real satisfaction from it.\nConstant stimulation from the digital world overactivates our \"wanting\" system (dopamine) but makes our \"pleasure\" system (opioids) less sensitive. Result: we keep seeking rewards but never feel truly satisfied.\nThe mental conflict is frustrating: people understand that scrolling social media or consuming endless entertainment is pointless, but they can't stop. Fisher calls this \"powerless reflexivity\" - you know what you should do but remain trapped in behaviors that harm you.\nThis is a specific consequence of late capitalism that has created an environment of constant stimulation never seen before in human history, where seeking gratification becomes compulsive but never satisfying.",
        "links": [
          "https://www.ultimavoce.it/mark-fisher-salute-mentale-come-lotta-politica/#google_vignette",
          "https://www.artribune.com/editoria/2023/02/realismo-capitalista-mark-fisher-libro-xxi-secolo/"
        ],
        "files": []
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "nweug8dn",
      "x": 1440,
      "y": -518.873220246825,
      "w": 320,
      "h": 485,
      "group": null,
      "data": {
        "date": "2025-09-19",
        "title": "Hypnosis",
        "type": "Finding",
        "action": "Exploring",
        "mainArea": "Speculation",
        "areas": [
          "Neuroscience",
          "Human-computer interaction",
          "Critical technology studies",
          "Society studies"
        ],
        "tags": [],
        "desc": "Hypnosis shows that our thinking isn't as stable as we think. When hypnotized, people accept ideas they would normally reject. This lets us create mental conflicts in a controlled way to see how the mind deals with them. Surprisingly, these conflicts can actually help people change in ways that wouldn't be possible otherwise. But this makes us wonder: if suggestions can so easily get past our logical thinking, how much control do we really have over our daily decisions?",
        "links": [
          "https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15994228/",
          "https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15964211/"
        ],
        "files": []
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "nfaki92h",
      "x": 1436,
      "y": 82,
      "w": 320,
      "h": 507,
      "group": null,
      "data": {
        "date": "2025-09-19",
        "title": "Devil shift",
        "type": "Finding",
        "action": "Exploring",
        "mainArea": "Speculation",
        "areas": [
          "Neuroscience",
          "Biopolitics",
          "Society studies"
        ],
        "tags": [],
        "desc": "The devil shift reflects a universal bias: we tend to see opponents as more hostile, threatening, and powerful than they really are, seeking evidence to confirm this view while ignoring anything that challenges it.\nThe angel shift is the opposite bias: we idealize allies, seeing them as more virtuous, trustworthy, and capable than they actually are, while overlooking their flaws or mistakes.",
        "links": [
          "https://biblio.liuc.it/ebookliuc/978-88-941811-0-4.pdf",
          "https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/journal-of-public-policy/article/abs/dealing-with-bad-guys-actor-and-processlevel-determinants-of-the-devil-shift-in-policy-making/81FAE1C9A099215FDE4CE73157E4B3CE"
        ],
        "files": []
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "nmm5bb23",
      "x": 1452,
      "y": 666,
      "w": 320,
      "h": 583,
      "group": null,
      "data": {
        "date": "2025-09-19",
        "title": "Cognitive overload",
        "type": "Finding",
        "action": "Exploring",
        "mainArea": "Speculation",
        "areas": [
          "Neuroscience",
          "Human-computer interaction",
          "Biopolitics",
          "Cyberpsychology",
          "Critical technology studies",
          "Society studies"
        ],
        "tags": [],
        "desc": "It has been established that as cognitive overload increases, so does the feeling of anxiety and avoidance when it comes to making decisions. This can trigger decision fatigue.\nThe quality of decisions deteriorates as cognitive resources are depleted; ultimately, this leads to outright decision avoidance or a tendency to delegate choices, even important ones. When the amount of information exceeds the threshold of available cognitive resources, they begin to compete with each other.",
        "links": [
          "https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6119549/",
          "https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0306457323002194",
          "https://arno.uvt.nl/show.cgi?fid=183529"
        ],
        "files": []
      }
    },
